explanation:
For a MISRA-dead-code analysis we must know which operations in OS_SocketSendTo are actually observable and whether any executed statement could be removed without changing program behaviour. Each listed symbol affects control flow, side-effects, or observable state in the target function:

- OS_CHECK_POINTER
  - These macros/funcs perform the initial parameter validation and may return/abort early; if they always trap/return then subsequent code would be dead. Need definition/behavior to determine reachability of later code.

- OS_CHECK_SIZE
  - Same as above for buflen size checks; affects whether the main body can be executed.

- OS_ObjectIdGetById
  - Determines whether the success branch (the bulk of the function) is entered; its return values and side-effects (e.g., refcounting) are essential to know if calls/assignments inside are ever executed or if they are effectively dead.

- OS_ObjectIdRelease
  - Released token is executed on the success path; if this is a no-op or has side-effects, removing it may change behaviour. Need its semantics to judge removability.

- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit
  - Part of ObjectIdGetById internals (transaction/init semantics) that can introduce observable side-effects (locking/refcount changes) even if caller doesn't use the result; needed to reason about whether the call to ObjectIdGetById can be removed.

- OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel
  - Internal cleanup path for failed transactions; required to understand whether ObjectIdGetById always has side-effects even on failure (relevant to dead-code determination).

- OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish
  - Internal finish used by ObjectIdRelease; may have side-effects (release/finalize) whose removal would change behaviour.

- OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex
  - Used in ObjectId lookup/validation; affects whether a valid token can be produced and thus whether downstream code runs; needed to reason about reachability.

- OS_ObjectIdConvertToken
  - Converts internal token forms; may influence whether OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET yields a valid stream pointer; needed to determine if table access is meaningful.

- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken
  - Used (directly or indirectly) to index the object table; must know mapping from token to table index to judge whether OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET/stream access is meaningful or always yields a fixed value.

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET
  - Macro/function that reads the stream table using the token/index; needed to know if the read is observable or could be removed (i.e., if it has side-effects or always yields the same value).

- OS_stream_table
  - The data structure being read; contents and possible invariants (e.g., socket_type distributions) are required to decide whether branches (incorrect type vs. impl call) are reachable.

- OS_stream_internal_record_t
  - Definition (layout) — specifically the socket_type member — is required to know how the code examines object state and whether that inspection is meaningful.

- OS_SocketSendTo_Impl
  - The actual implementation called on the success/datagram path; its observable side-effects determine if calling it matters. If it is a no-op, the call might be dead; if it has side-effects, removing it would change behaviour.

- OS_SocketType_DATAGRAM
  - The constant used in the type check; we need its value/meaning and any invariants about socket objects to decide if the comparison can ever be true/false (i.e., if one branch is dead).

- OS_SUCCESS
  - The success return-code constant used to guard the success path; must know its value and whether ObjectIdGetById can return it.

- OS_ERR_INCORRECT_OBJ_TYPE
  - The error assigned when the socket type mismatches; knowing whether this assignment is reachable or removable depends on how often/ever the condition can occur.

- OS_LOCK_MODE_REFCOUNT
  - Parameter passed to ObjectIdGetById that affects lookup/locking/refcount semantics; needed to know if different modes would change behaviour (and thus whether the call is required).

- LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE
  - The object type constant passed to ObjectIdGetById; defines which table/validation is done and therefore whether ObjectIdGetById can succeed for this id.

In short: to determine whether any executed operation in OS_SocketSendTo can be removed without affecting program behaviour, you must inspect the parameter-check macros, the object lookup/release implementations and their side-effects, the object-table access macro and table contents, the stream struct (socket_type) and constants controlling branching, and the implementation of the delegated send (OS_SocketSendTo_Impl). Without these symbols/definitions you cannot soundly conclude that any executed statement in the function is dead code.
